:"1346","1433":"1433","1385":"1385","1440":"1440","1372":"1372","1360":"1360","1370":"1370","1380":"1380","1390":"1390","Bolton, Lancashire, England":"Bolton, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom","Ormskirk, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom":"Ormskirk, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom","Blainsciough, Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, England, United Kingdom","Bolton, , Lancashire, England":"Bolton, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"De","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Worthington","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Lancashire, Cheshire, and Staffordshire): habitational name from any of the places in Lancashire and Leicestershire named Worthington. The placenames probably derive from an Old English personal name <i>Weorth</i> + Old English connective <i>-ing-</i> + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’.","History: Nicholas Worthington emigrated from England to Old Saybrook, CT, <i>c.</i> 1650."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Margaret De Worthington was born in 1360, in Ormskirk, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom, her father, Thomas De Worthington, was 23 and her mother, Marjory De Copull, was 14. She married Ellis de Bradshaw in 1380, in Bolton, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died in 1403, in Bolton, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 43."},"et":{"1360–1403":"1360–1403","1370–1440":"1370–1440","1372–Male":"1372–Surnud","1358–1403":"1358–1403","1385–1433":"1385–1433","1338–1390":"1338–1390","1346–Female":"1346–Surnud","1338":"1338","1403":"1403","1358":"1358","1346":"1346","1433":"1433","1385":"1385","1440":"1440","1372":"1372","1360":"1360","1370":"1370","1380":"1380","1390":"1390","Bolton, Lancashire, England":"Bolton, Lancashire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Ormskirk, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom":"Ormskirk, Lancashire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Blainsciough, Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Bolton, , Lancashire, England":"Bolton, Lancashire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1360–1403":"1360–1403","1370–1440":"1370–1440","1372–Male":"1372–Kuollut","1358–1403":"1358–1403","1385–1433":"1385–1433","1338–1390":"1338–1390","1346–Female":"1346–Kuollut","1338":"1338","1403":"1403","1358":"1358","1346":"1346","1433":"1433","1385":"1385","1440":"1440","1372":"1372","1360":"1360","1370":"1370","1380":"1380","1390":"1390","Bolton, Lancashire, England":"Bolton, Lancashire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Ormskirk, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom":"Ormskirk, Lancashire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Blainsciough, Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Bolton, , Lancashire, England":"Bolton, Lancashire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1360–1403":"1360–1403","1370–1440":"1370–1440","1372–Male":"1372–Décédé","1358–1403":"1358–1403","1385–1433":"1385–1433","1338–1390":"1338–1390","1346–Female":"1346–Décédée","1338